               <interp inst="t18470614-1548" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18470614"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18470614-1548" type="date" value="18470614"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470614-1548-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1548-18470614 t18470614-1548-offence-1 t18470614-1548-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1548. <persName id="def1-1548-18470614" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1548-18470614" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1548-18470614" type="age" value="45"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1548-18470614" type="surname" value="GRIFFIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1548-18470614" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM GRIFFIN</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470614-1548-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470614-1548-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470614-1548-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing 6 half-crowns, 3 shillings, and 4 pence, the monies of <persName id="t18470614-name-1204" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1204" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1204" type="surname" value="LINDSEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1204" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470614-1548-offence-1 t18470614-name-1204"></join>Samuel Lindsey</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1205" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1205" type="surname" value="LINDSEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1205" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL LINDSEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a grocer, and live in New-cut, Lambeth. The prisoner was seven months in my service, and came as a single man, but he is married—he lived in the house till within about six weeks or two months—I frequently missed articles from the stock, and watched a female who came on Saturday the 15th of May, she came to the shop when we were very busy—she did not ask for anything, but tendered him half-a-sovereign—he gave her 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. out of it—I stopped him, and asked him if he knew her—he said, certainly not, that he never saw her before in his life—she said not ask for anything—he gave her 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. worth of goods, and gave her 18<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. out of a half-sovereign—I charged him with robbing me—the women said in his presence that it was a sovereign she gave him—she bolted off, and never came back—I went to the prisoner's lodging and asked for him—they said he was not within—I asked for Mr. Griffin, they said she was within, and to my surprise I found a wife and three children—I had previously seen two or three sove<lb></lb>reigns and two half-sovereigns in the till, and the half-sovereign he put in would make three half-sovereigns—I stood by him, and am certain he took half-a-sovereign from her—I found half-a-sovereign more in the till than there was a minute before—the women left her basket behind her—she went away to fetch a witness to prove she had a sovereign—I found from four to six pounds of sugar at the prisoner's lodging—I cannot swear to it—having received half-a-sovereign, the prisoner pretended to give change for a sovereign—he gave more than the change.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> He lived with you four months? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, from the 20th of Sept.—he lived in the house with me most of the time—he had left off sleeping there—he left my service once, came again in a fortnight or three week, and wished to come back—I took him in, and then he proposed to live out of the house—if I had known he was married I would not have taken him—I cannot recollect whether there were two or three sovereigns in the till, but there were three half-sovereigns—I had looked just before the transaction, and know there were no more sovereigns, and I looked at it afterwards—there was probably 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver there—it was a little after eleven o'clock at night—I had four persons serving in the shop—there is more than one till—the shopmen would put gold into the till, and take it out if they wanted change—after the woman found that I detected it she said she had given him a sovereign—we had seen her very often at the place—the prisoner was at the bottom of the counter—she came right through the shop down to him—I went and stood next to him—I cannot say now whether I told him to attend to the customer—when we are busy he serves—I sometimes do call him—there were ten or twelve customer in the shop at the time—I stood close to him—what he received from her he dropped into the till—our rule is to put gold on the counter, and take the change out, but he opened the till, and dropped in what he took before he took out the change—I did not change him with receiving it as a farthing—I thought it was a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184706140218"></xptr>
               <p>farthing when it was first given—I did not say, "Was not that a farthing you received?"—I saw it on the middle of the counter when she laid it down—he gave her 1/2 lb. of tea, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. (six ounces and two ounces) and 2lb. of 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. sugar—the tea was in separate parcels, 6oz. and 2oz., but it was out of the same canister—he put the change on the counter—it was six half-crowns, three shillings, and four pence—she was in the act of taking it up—she had not taken up any part of it—she laid her basket on the counter, and was going to take it up when I interposed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-1206" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1206" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1206" type="surname" value="UNDERWOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-1206" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN UNDERWOOD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I took the prisoner in charge—I saw a female at the prisoner's lodging—she appeared before the Magistrate—the prisoner said going to the station that he did not know the female, nor was she his wife—after locking him up, Mr. Lindsey and I went to his lodgings, and inquired if Mr. Griffin lived there, they said "Yes"—we asked if Mr. Griffin was at home, they said "Yes," and called her down.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">cross-examined. Q.</hi> You had not seen the women before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LINDSEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I saw her at the lodgings, and we had watched her previously to the lodgings, which we knew were the prisoner's.</p>
               <p>
